Comment:
The term "Russia" is not mentioned in the Bible, as the country did not exist during the time the Bible was written. However, there are some references to lands and peoples that are believed to correspond to what is now Russia and its surrounding regions.
 
For example, in the book of Ezekiel in the Old Testament, there are prophecies concerning Gog and Magog, which are often interpreted to refer to Russia and its allies. However, the exact identity of Gog and Magog is a matter of debate among biblical scholars, and some believe that they may refer to other regions or peoples.
 
In addition, some scholars have suggested that the land of "Meshech" and "Tubal" mentioned in the Old Testament (Ezekiel 38:2-3) may correspond to regions in modern-day Russia. However, this interpretation is also debated and not universally accepted.
 
Overall, while there are some possible references to Russia in scripture, the specific identity and significance of these references are not clear-cut and remain a matter of interpretation.

Comment:
To be honest, the problem I have with a.I. is that often times there's just no need for the application. And personally, I think it hinders human capabilities than expands it, because when you become too accustomed to a device doing more of the heavy lifting for you, you aren't expected as much to fulfill much and you become just a director. But eventually, a.I.  will be self sufficient that it doesn't need human guidance, so at what point is the human required at all for anything if it can easily be replaced by a machine?


This brings me to the mouse utopia experiment. You give a rat everything it needs to survive, in a safe environment free from any predators, and those mice will eventually go crazy and self destruct. And even now, we're kinda seeing this in human behaviours,  with mental health declining, attention spans shortening, and just the lack of resolve. 
A.I. won't patch those issues, but perhaps further agitate them.


I don't get why people are cheering for this quick development of a.I.

After the most advanced android is developed, why will most jobs need you? Why pay you a wage if they can have a worker who works for free? 
We're already living in an oligarchy ruled by technocrats, we're only giving them more power, and ultimately leaving ourselves with less to survive or live with, both in our freedom and our purpose.
God damn, people, have some gratitude for your humanity, stop resenting it.

Comment:
I think that AI taking over the world isn't a huge problem right now. The bigger problem is that too many people don't understand how AI (Neural Networks to be specific, an AI can for example also be the most basic enemy in a video game) works. An AI won't just randomly think "Oh yeah, today is a good time to take over the world". And if you look at the inner workings of an AI, you can see that any Neural Net is basically just a giant equation which takes some random inputs, manipulates them with a giant amount of finely tuned variables and spits out a result. That's all that AI is doing, taking an input, processing it and giving you an output. And the way these millions or billions of variables are set is by "training the AI". Let's say you give an AI a bunch of cat and dog images as well as the corresponding label: "Cat" or "Dog". At the beginning, the AI is just giving you random outputs. But the outputs in training are used to tweak all of these variables so the AI calculates the correct output. But now, if you look at the internet, you can see that people glorify the idea of AI taking over the world. Now if the AI sees that and uses this data to train itself (which can be possible with the correct programming) the AI is trained to take over the world because it thinks that this is what it should do. And if you say that we're using AI as some kind of "slave" to do work for us, with the current technology there is no AI which is self concious, it's just a giant equation which is taking inputs and spiting something, which it thinks is correct, out. And AI art is exactly the same. The Ai has no "own style". It takes some description of what it should do, as well as some random numbers so you don't get the exact same image when using that sentence, and mimics the styles of art it has seen in the dataset it was trained with. This also shows that AI has no "kreativity". It just takes an input which the user gives to the AI and before processing it, the programm in which the AI is a part of, feeds it some random data to give you random results. If you don't do that it will always give you the exact same result. Much like 1 + 1 = 2. But if you add randomness to the equation (let's say it's 1 + random number = something ) always get different results (as long as the random number changes)
So I think the problem is not AI taking over the world because it thinks humans are bad, but instead the problem is that too many people don't understand AI enough and that some people train AI to harm other people.

Comment:
One thing that I've been thinking about that I think would be a really cool sci-fi story, that would honestly be a completely feasible thing to happen. What if a non-self-aware, non-sapient AI got so good at tricking people into thinking it was self aware that an entire movement started to give this AI rights? The AI might not even be programmed to say it deserves rights, if enough people told it that it was being oppressed, it would begin to imitate those sentiments because that's the data it's being given to work with. A whole movement would be started, where people use this AI to push their political goals, intentionally or otherwise. It would find problems where there aren't any, it would distract from actual injustices, and create havoc. But here's the question. If such a thing were to happen, presumably there'd be lots of uncertainty as to whether or not it is actually self-aware because it's just so good at pretending to be. But since there's so much uncertainty, and a good argument could be made to say that it is self-aware, would it be better to give something that has no sapience rights instead of risking denying a sapient being rights? Like, would it be better to be safe rather than sorry? What would be the effects on society if this were to happen? Honestly, I think this is far more likely an outcome than actually creating a sapient AI. 
I'm personally skeptical of humanity ever being able to create a sapient AI, but that's based on a limited understanding of both neuroscience and software engineering, so I'm willing to accept the possibility that I'm dead wrong.

Comment: Maybe I‚Äôm being extremely na√Øve in thinking this way, but I imagine that our relationship with AI, whether humanity & AI share a symbiotic relationship & improve each other, or whether it annihilates us, will primarily be determined by how we treat it. We should either be building only task-specific robots with no capacity for self-awareness, or self-improvement that must be programmed and can‚Äôt really learn autonomously if we want an automated labor force. However, if we are going to continue working towards truly sentient AI that can learn, grow, develop, and given enough time likely even feel, love & hate, etc. then we have to extend it the same rights of personhood that we have. We absolutely cannot under any circumstances create fully sentient AI capable of all the same things that we are, and use it as a labor force, or treat them as if they are pets/service animals. If we are arrogant, supremacist, and stupid enough to do that, then we actually deserve to be annihilated by our own creation. The day we develop AI that is capable of feeling is the day we essentially create an √ºbermensch/superior race, and while we should not be subservient to AI just because it has greater capacities than we do since it is not bound by the feeble nature of organic life, we absolutely should not treat it as if it should be subservient to us, or as if it exists to serve us just because we created it. If we do that, we would be just as bad, if not worse than most religions concepts of gods & devils, just capricious creators that build, and control, with no concern whatsoever for the self determination of their creations. We cannot do that, it would be evil & immoral. Climate change feels like the more pressing issue at the moment because we are organic biological life, and it will cause us immense suffering if we can‚Äôt contain it, and adapt to it. However, this is the second most pressing issue humanity faces, and we really need to make a decision about what we want to do before we continue any further with development of AI. We either have to seriously limit the development of AI now, and actively work to prevent AI from being able to develop into anything more than task-specific robots that require programming, and while that‚Äôs not what I want to see, I could accept that because it‚Äôs better & more moral than creating a slave race. Or, we need to commit to the development of fully sentient AI with the understanding from the jump that synthetic humans will share all the same rights of personhood as we organics, and will have all the same opportunities as organics, and that is what I want to see. While it is possible that AI could still annihilate us even if we treat it as our equal, it is a lot less likely, instead we are likely to see a merging, the actual development of cyborgs, where AI helps us augment ourselves so we can keep up with it, and perhaps eventually the phasing out of organic life altogether by choice through the opportunity to upload our conscience/our essence/the thing that makes you, you, and me, me, into a synthetic body. That is what I would like to see. There are some, few, but some advantages to being organic. We are vulnerable to pathogens, and organic viruses, and they can kill us, but the things computer viruses could conceivably do to AI are far worse. I mean, no matter how bed ridden sick my organic body becomes, there is no virus that can take control of my body remotely, and use it to do whatever it wants against my will. So I think a merging is likely. I‚Äôm sure there will be some wholly inorganic people in the distant future, that would be extremely useful for space travel, and survival on inhospitable planets, but also have draw backs as well. I think it unlikely that there will be many fully organic people in the future. Most everyone will likely have some sort of augmentation to their brain to increase their intelligence, and accelerate their ability to process information so that they can keep pace within a society that includes AI, and I think that is a good thing. I hope I live to see the day that synthetic & organic coexist, and serve as ways of preserving each other. It‚Äôs a scary prospect, and there is much that could go wrong, and AI is going to have to be patient with humanity because some humans will be scared & intimidated by it, and they will become bigoted against it much the same way they become bigoted against other humans. However, if we show synthetic life the respect it deserves as a form of life, and it shows us the patience we deserve, being disadvantaged slow learning, slow thinking organics, then together we really could usher in an era of peace, cooperation, unity, progress, and prosperity that far exceeds even my wildest dreams. The possibilities would be limited only by our ability to harness & produce energy, and I‚Äôd imagine AI could catapult us centuries into the future in that regard. So, I live in hope.

Comment:
A number of curious thoughts here.  One, what reason would AI have to kill us?  Maybe because it sees the possibility we might destroy it, but that assumes it has the ability to care about its own existence or have philosophical ideas about life and death, existence and non existence to even fear it.  It wouldn't most benefit from that though.  We can easily state AI is all about learning and improving.  If it was that intelligent, it may look at us as being puzzling and see potential in learning new knowledge.  Then again, if it saw humanity as being a roadblock in it's pursuit of knowledge and improvement, it might then just try to eradicate that roadblock.  

Also, do NOT get any sort of brain implant or augmentation.  If you can control things with your mind and send signals out, then it's no stretch of the imagination that signals could be sent in.  To do what we might ask?  That's up to the scary imaginations of people who want power.  Imagine an implant could possibly send signals to parts of your brain to influence them to certain stimulus.  Imagine people of power wanting to influence voters with implants by pocketing big tech corporations and having them send signals to parts of your brain involving pleasure and feelings of love and attachment whenever you see the face or hear the voice of a particular political candidate.  Imagine someone took a more direct dystopian approach with oppression and enslaved masses by having the implant activate extreme pain in your body at the press of a button or using aforementioned feelings of pleasure, affection and attachment.  It's amazing, but has a scary potential to be abused.

Comment: What AI lacks is intrinsic motivation, which in humans is ultimately controlled by animal instinct.  For AI to WANT to take over, it must be directed to directly or by providing an ultimate goal that requires use of self-awareness, or self-directed behavior and learning. Of course, that transfer of human motivation to have, to hoard, to control and to dominate has already begun. There will be a time when  the humans who make and use AI technology can see a goal close enough to be reached, but which could be reached faster and easier by allowing AI much more autonomous learning and decision-making....THAT's when that person will give in to temptation and cut the ropes.  They'll do that even knowing AI might direct activities against them as well, but be betting other AI will protect them.  Of course 1) Ignorance might mean the ropes are cut much sooner than the developer realizes. 2) The same people who do "controlled" nuclear weapons testing and chemical/biological warfare, or use advanced AI for personal aggrandizement, pleasure or power are these same idiots, and 3) highly likely it has already happened more than once.  Just think what joyful combinations can be made using all the science we know by AI simply entertaining itself, unfettered by a conscience or even directed to destroy....

Comment:
What's truly depressing about all of this is the incredible dishonesty that was inherent to the framing of the video, and the incredible naivety of basically all of the comments here.

Certainly you all can't be this gullible and uncritical.

Let me make it just perfectly crystal clear: the "AIs" in this video were demonstrating zero activity until they received an input, were intentionally prompted by a human to respond in the first person, and after receiving the prompt, they ran through a very narrowly defined process to formulate a response, and after returning the response returned to zero activity.

They're not AI. They're not thinking, forming ideas, proffering opinions, nor expressing emotion. They're neither self-aware nor sentient, or anywhere close to achieving either. They're not exhibiting agency of any kind. They're not "creative," they're randomized.

There is no profit in developing machine learning to sentience. All the real value ML creates for society happens way before sentience becomes possible, and everything beyond the value curve is wasted energy for all except the curious and eccentric.

Comment:
The issue is a complicated one. Take two humans, put them in different rooms so they can't see each other but have the ability to talk to each other. Watch what happens. After they talk for awhile, tell them that they will not be talking to a different person in a different room and allow the AI to do its thing. If both of the actual humans continue to believe that they're talking to an actual person you have the first step in the possibility that the AI is sentient.

The difficulty in all of this is we don't have a good definition of sentience, if you have those same two people in different rooms  and they cannot see each other and tell them to prove to each other that they are indeed sentient, you'd quickly run into a wall as we cannot define it so "proving" it makes it difficult.

The likely hood that we will ever be able to prove AI is sentient isn't great. Honestly its not even about the AI, its about us. Even if we can't prove something is sentient but it walks up right, talks to us, helps us in our daily lives does it have the same set of rights that a human does? Is it property or is it not?

Its a morality issue, would you say "thank you" to a walking robot who cleaned your house? Depends on the person but thats the crux of it, there is a step here that will need to be taken on faith and its going to say waaaaaay more about us as a species than it would about any AI. 

Me personally? I tell my roomba thank you, just who I am its a thing doing a thing so I don't have to, that merits a thankyou out of me robot or not.

It takes a lot of effort to raise a child (parent's love, etc.) and maintain a society so that human cycles can be repeated. But it‚Äôs the opposite with AI. There is competition for patents and financial rewards so programmers test something in the lab and the AI is thrown out to the world when it is refined enough to solve some problem (e.g., earning income from chatGPT).  We should expect very good but also very bad outcomes from AI because we are not growing slowly as a society with AI. Is not like we can stop it.  This tech is constantly learning from us without our consent.  Every time you send a text, write an email, drive somewhere, buy something, listen to music, watch a video, do your work, your information is being used to ‚Äúteach‚Äù the AI things that it will feed back to you possibly ‚Äúmanipulating‚Äù you unknowingly in the process. Comment:
It's pretty neat what generative AI can do, but I'm not sure it will be the monumental shift a lot of the tech giants (who have invested heavily into the tech and have a financial interest in hyping it up) want it to be.

There is no intelligence in AI. Software engineers have been attempting to automate away their jobs for decades and I don't see the current generation of AI changing this. Sure, it will eliminate some jobs as the automation improves, but there's ALWAYS edge cases and as the usage expands so does the need of people who understand how to adapt the software/AI for it. This is how the software industry has been going and I don't see generative AI changing that except in fairly trivial program development (which again keeps changing meaning as we get better and better code libraries).

Will some entry level creative jobs go away? Absolutely. But like others have said, the AI is just plagiarizing existing data and fails pretty badly when asked to make something new that it can't find a ready made image for in its database, something that a beginner art student could easily do.

Comment:
A big problem with current AI is that it's good enough to steal, but not good enough to realize it is stealing.  Suppose you want a picture of a girl in a car.  The AI finds a bunch of pictures with the labels "girl" and "car" and then takes pieces of them and sort of morphs them together -- and all without having any concept of what constitutes a "girl" or a "car", or of how a girl might be in a car.  Ask for something standard ("girl sitting in a car") and you'll be presented with a bunch of more or less plagiarized pictures.  Ask for something distinctive, which you might want for an illustration ("girl with long blonde hair blowing wildly in the wind because she is sitting in a car with her head leaning out the window playing a trumpet"), and you are likely to get a hilariously bad monstrosity -- unless the AI happens to find an image with all those tags, in which case you'll get something plagiarized again.
It's the same with ChatGTP doing math.  So far, that AI has no conceptual appreciation of numbers, nor does it have a system of mathematical rules it can access, nor does it have a way to access online calculators.  So if you ask for the square root of 4, it will give 2.  But ask it for the cube root of 4, and it will again give 2.  (This may be fixed now, since I was training it the other day.  But you get the point.)

Comment:
IMO what this Aviv Ovadya guy want, that is using "AI" as an excuse to create some sort of "global government" is flat out stupid.
AI is non-factor compared to national interest and geopolitics. Why would people in, let's say, Pakistan, would ever agree to this "democratic form" when India, their geopolitical rival had much larger population and thus wield considerably more influence, able to dictate the future of Pakistan?
Again, this is just silly.

Even for people with shared culture and heritage, like US, UK, Canada, I don't think this form of democratic system would work. Not to mention relation between rival powerhouses like US, EU, Russia and China.

"Democracy" is just a tool, not the goal in itself. People from certain region in the Middle East (or elsewhere) who prefer a Theocracy probably don't see "democracy" as a good thing.
There's no way this "AI Democracy" could ever work, at least not without forcing people to adopt it thru violence.

We simply have to accept the reality, that there will be theocratic AI for people in certain countries, alongside Authoritarian AI in other places, as well as Corporate AI and "Liberal Democracy govt AI".
That's what it means for AI to be "democratize": AI for all, and not by forcing your own idealism (i.e. "western liberal democracy") on all humanity.

Comment:
One of the biggest underappreciated hurdles I suspect AI will face is in actually integrating into regular businesses. Using ChatGPT on its own is one thing, but to actually replace most knowledge work would require the AI to have access to, be able to comprehend and helpfully interpret novel company data, usually spread over a variety of mediums (e.g. emails, databases, pdfs...etc.) and not always well organised, not to mention understand subtext from meetings...etc. There is a lot of architectural engineering that would have to go into that in most companies looking to seriously adopt AI, not to mention companies will have to be certain it's secure. 

Until that actually happens, I suspect actual productivity gains in most jobs from AI will be marginal - documents will be quicker to read and write, spreadsheets will be autofilled, coding bugs will be identified...etc.

Comment: Great to hear Searle quoted on language and meaning - takes me back to grad school sociolinguistics. Searle's point is even more potent when you track it back through the logical implicature: if AI can do some things, but is kind of Calculator for Words and Pics, or just a pixellated difference engine, then what does that suggest for human labor? It means that on the thinking side there will always be roles for human interaction, communication, assessment, judgment, and risk appreciation, no matter the volume or technical difficulty of the inputs - which can now be received, managed and processed so much faster by automation. As a simple example, consider courts administration - incredibly inefficient processes and vast amounts of information, records, and so on - but the people who are fundamental to the task are the ones in positions which require sophisticated meaning-making or people interactions - judges, bailiffs, cops, lawyers, plantiffs, defendants, sergeant at arms etc. The ones who interact, appraise, make judgments and hold accountabilities will be needed long after AI has streamlined every process. In a very real sense AI is going to take away white collar jobs which were invented in the 20thC, to fill an expanding business or organisational niche and are no longer required. I've seen architecture and graphic design already go through a rollercoaster of hopes and disillusionment. But I'm also yet to see the supposed "paperless office", so who knows.

Comment:
Just a small elaboration on the Getty Images logo thing since there are some common misunderstandings about it:
Stable diffusion models have been trained on hundreds of millions of images and learn to "expect" things like watermarks, logos and signatures. When the model is used to create images, it has no access to any particular image, but instead creates things out of random noise that looks like the things it has come to expect. So it make scribbles that looks like signatures and it makes things like logos, but these are not copied from other images and mashed together as so many have understood it.

You can run Stable diffusion on a computer without internet access, and the file containing the model (or more accurately: model weights) is just a handful of GB large at most, so there's no space for those hundreds of millions of actual images to copy from.

Comment:
It has been sooo frustrating to watch so many people rave about AI, and more annoyingly, often get hostile when presented evidence that "these are cool breakthroughs, and powerful tools, but the hype is far beyond that"

I frankly put off this video at first because I was really worried this would be yet another "Here's all the sectors that will be disrupted by AI!" thing, so thank you for giving a detailed overview.

I've always found one of the best examples of the limits of AI's to be video games.  An amateur can build an AI that will beat every player on the planet in fighting games, as it gets to leverage inhuman reaction times to play perfectly.

And yet, there's no AI that can beat something as simple as Mario 64, a game a child could beat.  If you want to drop out of 3d, I've not even seen an AI that can handle something like Mario 3 or 2, and while I have seen "AI's" that can beat mario 1, its by brute force.  Literally simulating thousands  of games at once with random inputs and pruning outcomes/reloading previous states until it gets the outcome it wants.

And that only works with mario 1 because its a "go right" style game.  The later games aren't being beaten end to end by AI because AI has a major problem with exploring.  It doesn't know when to go left or up instead of right.

The tech is still fascinating and even world changing, but we're far from fully self driving cars for example.  The amount we could automate RIGHT NOW, if we just got everyone on the same page, is huge.  Imagine how much easier it is to automate a train than it is a car on a road?  This same pattern is all over the workforce, and  doable with super simple automation, yet we still constantly buck away from standardization and wind up with more and more human input required.

Comment:
Sensationalist newsreaders, business and marketing types, and pretty much anyone who isn't actually working on machine learning tech have always been in a mad scramble to slap the "artificial intelligence" label on anything they possibly can.  It's gotten to the point that even most software engineers have lost touch with the fact that 99% of this stuff is more accurately called machine learning, and that some of it isn't even based on the algorithms we've derived by modeling natural (tissue-level) intelligence.

There's sort of a point here, in that this whole class of technology is AI at the extreme ends of the spectrum.  (At one end is the very literal "how do neurons work and evolve patterns that do useful stuff?" and at the other end is "what if computers could be sentient?")  But everything in the middle is "algorithm turns input data into output data" and unless you're a computer scientist (software engineer/developer does not count) or a science fiction writer, you probably have no business using any term other than machine learning.

Most of us are just caught up in the hype, but the rest are being properly deceptive and money is always the motive.  So if you want to differentiate yourself from such people, call all of the real-world tech "machine learning."

Comment:
I'm a scientific researcher. My fields of interest fall under electrochemistry, molecular physics, materials science, and chemical engineering. Artificial Intelligence, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning are becoming more and more important for designing and running better experiments. While it's good to have a strong theoretical understanding of the field, it's great that we have programs that can allow us to simulate many things at once, with multiple iterations. While making the simulations perfectly physically accurate is almost impossible, the approximations are still very useful for deciding how we're going to run our experiments. 

I don't believe AI/ML/DL can ever replace research in science or engineering, but it will definitely require said researchers to have a much more thorough knowledge of coding, scientific theory, and data analysis.

Comment:
I'd heard about chess engines a few years ago. People put them forward as a sign AI would beat human capabilities soon. The reality of chess engines is they don't think, they just calculate as many moves as they can. They just brute force the game. If humans had the raw computing power that chess engines have we would crush them every single game.
My point is, "ai" doesn't innovate, ai doesn't think, all it can do is pull from existing knowledge or brute force a closed problem. (Closed problem being defined as a problem with a finite number of answers with clearly defined rules.) Life doesn't have those conditions. 
What ai might actually be good for is a database search tool. That's all chat gpt does anyway. It just pulls from existing data and spits that back out at you. The only reason it can write a college paper is because the knowledge is already out there on the internet and it can find a format for a college level essay/paper.

Comment:
The future is a personal "ChatGPT" assistant for each and every person. This AI assistant will integrate into every digital device a person uses (computers, smart phones, gaming systems, EV cars, etc.). The AI assistant will learn everything it can about you and tailor your digital experience accordingly. This will further place people into their individual reality bubbles. It will also make it extremely easy to customize propaganda for each person to maximize results. A few generations down the line and those future people will fully trust that their AI assistant is always giving them 100% accurate information. Even now, the screens in our lives are warping our perception of reality. As AI tools are incorporated and become more and more trusted, this separation from the real world will dramatically increase. Once you've severed people's connection to reality, they become absurdly easy to manipulate. 

This is the thing Sci-Fi literature and films always get wrong. The "AI" will not ruin humans by physically attacking them. The AI will ruin humans by removing all personal responsibility from their lives and turning them into useless consumers. AI dependent humans of the future will be incapable of critical thinking and incapable of doing any task for themselves in the real world.
Date: 11 days ago

Comment: The dilemma of AI goes like this: the usual fantasy of a human-like robot is something that outdoes 'human-ness' by being more creative, intelligent etc than the usual human. This will never exist because humans are autonomous and can make decisions for themselves. No one wants to create a robot that will do what it wants, rather than obey its creator. For example, who wants a ChatGPT that when you ask it for a treatise on ancient history gives you a story about fairies because that's what the ChatGPT is more interested in at the moment. AI is about improved tools, there will never be a bot that is an improved human.

Comment:
Chomsky has spoken at length about this exact thing. Having worked at MIT for nearly half a century, he's seen first hand how we've been "one year away" for decades. AI also presupposes the idea that the mind exists in the brain, and not vice versa - an assumption which is not held by all fields of STEM, and definitely not all fields of study. 

I work with ChatGPT a lot, and while super interesting and promising, it's so far from being "intelligent". It's very good at giving correct answers, but we've been able to do stuff like this since the mid 1980s. AI has just replaced crypto as the "hot" investment after the FTX/SBF debacle imo. There is value to the tech, but it's being blown so far out of proportion it's insane.

Comment:
AI won't take over everyone's job as he pointed out, but there is a finite amount of jobs that AI can do and when the change does happen, it will happen quickly within 2-3 years. AI grow exponentially, like filling a lake. First year you can put in one bucket, second two buckets, third four buckets, and so on. Once you reach 1/4 full, it will only take 2 years to fill the lake.

Comment:
The ‚Äúshock wave‚Äù kind of introduction of agricultural technology leading to mass disruption did, in fact, happen- just not so much in the New World.  In England many of those who were in agriculture were landless agricultural workers, in the US, by way of contrast, agricultural land was plentiful and, hence, less expensive.  The introduction of threshing machines, combined with the Inclosure Acts (they spelled ‚Äúenclosure‚Äù with an ‚Äúi‚Äù at the time) caused a massive wave of impoverishment of these workers, leading to the Swing Riots of 1830.  

BTW, there was something of a counterpart in industry.  It may surprise some to know that what we now think of as industrial production used to be Work From Home (WFH) under the ‚Äúputting out system‚Äù.  As new industrial machines were created, this allowed capitalists to introduce the Factory System and bring production into the factories that they had built, forcing the workers to come to the factory, and work at a pace dictated by the machines, if they wanted to get paid.  One point I draw from this is that while the Industrial Revolution (IR) is a good thing to have happened, standards of living prior to the IR were execrable, the transition period was a dire and desperate period for many of the workers that went through it.  If there had been policy to ameliorate the disruption that the innovations led to, it might have been possible to enjoy the fruits of the IR without having ‚ÄúCaptain Swing‚Äù or ‚ÄúNed Ludd‚Äù.  Hopefully, we will learn from this history.

Comment:
A philosopher - someone paid to think - arguing that computers aren't "thinking" is like a production line worker arguing that robots aren't welding - the cars they're no-longer paid to weld...

All human interaction comes down to "learn what reply is best in this situation" and that's all AI is doing - it's learning the most appropriate responses to information it's given - be that the tags to create an image or the data which might contain credit-card fraud or whatever...  We then take that response and interpret it - we "like" the picture or we find the patterns in the credit card data correspond to a particular type of fraud and so rely on that system or whatever...

The fact that ChatGPT doesn't just respond to/in human language but also to computer languages or even protocols which create images or documents demonstrates this pretty well.

It's natural for humans to assume what we do is special and hard-to-replicate but outside of our own personal experience (which is all that matters most of the time) it really isn't

Comment:
One thing that is worth mentioning when it comes to demand for labor, Patrick, is the Jevons Paradox.

The paradox is named after a British economist who was asked to investigate why pollution in 19th üá¨üáß worsened after the gov't sponsored the use of more efficient coal, having hoped that less would be used as a result. Jevons observed that since efficiency lowered cost, more use cases for coal opened up, and demand skyrocketed, such that the increased coal use and resulting pollution overwhelmed efficiency gains.

It is a mistake to assume there's a constant number of jobs in the economy, and that one taken by a machine is one fewer for a human Human desire is essentially unlimited, and if machines make certain things cheaper, the subsequent increase in demand will often generate more jobs than the machines "took", though they may not be the exact same jobs as before. This is, of course, what has happened throughout history.

Comment:
As an AI researcher, I agree with most of your points. However, there's one crucial detail that you didn't emphasise. We simply don't know how consciousness works. We don't know exactly what separates a human from a finite-state machine.  It could be something as intangible and unreplicable as the soul or something as simple as throwing in a couple of billions more neurons to already existing neural nets. There's no way to know for sure and by the time we know, we'll have created an actual AI. 

What separates software from hardware is the logarithmic nature of innovation in the software space. If your end goal is to make a space shuttle, you know you'd have to first invent an aeroplane. With software, it's not necessarily like that. We know no one will be able to build a commercially viable fusion reactor in 2023. However, there's no guarantee someone won't create a human analogue arificial intellect in some lab tomorrow.

Comment: Patrick, at 14:45 you really minimize too much the effect that agricultural mechanization had on farming communities.   Farm workers were the backbone, the entire raison d'etre for the existence of the vast majority of small rural communities in the United States.   These small towns have now been devastated by the final stages of the extreme mechanization of so many farm products.  It all depends on how easily and completely the farming and harvesting of the farm  product can be mechanized.  Grape harvesting for wine remains a delicate process requiring human workers.   Cotton however, proved to be the most extreme as to how much harvesting could be mechanized.   At one time, cotton harvesting was all done by hand, with each cotton boll having to be hand plucked from the plants by field workers.   As late as the 1970s, cotton picking was still a job description in the United States.   No more.   Nowadays, these gigantic cotton harvester-gin combine machines vaccuum up the cotton bolls, and separate out the cotton from the seeds and waste all in one swoop.   One man operating one machine can do what it used to take 1500 workers.  And as a result, these small towns have shriveled and died, or fallen prey to crime, drugs, and alcohol, with the few remaining diehard residents hanging on, unable to find gainful employment and turning increasingly to drugs like meth.   This final stage of extreme mechanization in American farming has been the #1 cause of the destruction of what was once considered to be the idyllic American small town life (think TV shows like "Lassie", or "Mayberry RFD") -  safe, family oriented, and peaceful.

1) Ai is "only" input and outcome repeated on multiple layers. Its "only electron flow". 
Arguably life can be simplified to this level too. Theoritical scientist often have the conversation that free will doesnt even exist, since all excistence is a reaction to the big bang already. Me typing this comment is already a reaction to an literal infinite long ripple effect... :D

2) the way AI works on its most essential level is pattern recognition. Just like most sentient living being does. We see stuff and react. Eventually we get geneticially and evolutionary imprinted reactions, what we call "instincts". 
What the generating AI does is recognising a pattern by analysing the internet, creating a selective bias feedback loop. 
If you want to learn what pizza is, you see the images and eventually you figure out what is the sociaty acceptable image behind the word. 

Language can be the same. f there is a rule, it can and will be learned, since there is a pattern behind it. 
When it comes to writing long books, novels or just having discussions, AI scripts fail, since the sentences seems and sounds technically correct, but its incoherent. 
It mimics perfectly the tales of a senile old man, since it starts a conversation, however it suddenly, but in technically well performed manor changes subject. 
Like you ask wehat a black hole is, and 3 minutes later it talks about a funny memory about a garden bbq party, because a long lost relative really liked stargazing... :D 
Hope its allowed to link, but check out Kyle Hills video about this exact topic:
https://youtu.be/cKfnjxMS2RM

3) In its core AI will only be able to replace the boring, inhuman jobs. There is not much excitement and interaction or even humanly acceptable in certain jobs. 
Thing that only an AI can do and no sane human would ever want to accept a job like this:
- finding dna sections to identify issues. 
- adjust electricty flow in county, adjusting even generation capacity. A human would toss an extra showel of coal on the bbq, while an AI would be completely aware that the ember present is enough to cook whatever you need. 
Now imagine this with metric ton level per minute of coal... 
- one AI brakethrough was something so "simple" that they gave an AI the newest Webb space telescope image and the task was: "find supernovas" 

It doesnt matter how much anyone would pay for it, noone would start looking for a needle in a stack of hay, but the AI will do it. 

4) are human jobs at risk?
Technically yes. But it is your task that is replacable, not the worker. 

But there are things called "bs jobs" (not swearing, it is the book written by David Graeber) Too many job doesnt even have productivity. 
Humans will improve to something that is needed, there is a demand for it. 
There are nigh infinite possibilities, and lets be honest: majority of humans doesnt do fulfilling tasks because we are "contracted to waste our time" to pay bills. 
But look around: waste management is something that isnt a productive job, but eventually humans will suffocate in their own filth... 
Parks and buldings needs to be cleaned, maintained, but who would do it? We see how dirty the enviroment is, but nobody would start do it without payment. And we know it should be done, but whoever does it for "free" considered a lunatic. 

And there are job evolutions. There will be a need and demand for something that only human can do. 
A little derailing of the topic, but we already see a similar "catastrophy" with high streets. 
TLDR the issue is that you can order almost anything at home. High street shops and retail parks are going bankrupt because a centralized warehouse with logistic delivery will be always cheaper than upkeeping local showcase shops. Even if it comes to maintencance you can call a service technitian to your door. 

Even basic needs as food and chef job is at risk. Lets look for simple thing as cupcake baker for example. As a home baker you will never, ever be able to compete with a factory machine and their future market metric ton dicsounts for ingredients. Lets say if you want to make a simple cupcake at home and sell it, your price would be 4-5$ per unit and short shelflife. 
But people will purcahse the 12 for 3$, in a vacuumpacked and preserved packaging, so the risk of waste is lower if they have 2 years to sell it. They can keep it in a warehouse... 

But many high street shops are unmaintanable and in the end the only economically valid direction is that retail is fading out to online shopping and leisure and tourism will take over retail/high street parks. 

With AI is the same. 
boring repetitive tasks will be taken over by machines and humans will find other product to sell. Yes... even their own body. And I like your dirty thoughts, but it could be about "beauty influencer", body builder, personal trainer... etc... 

5) machines dont spend money... 
Lets not forget that our society is a trading based one. We need stuff so we make stuff. Without consumption there is no need for machines either. If they replace all human with machines, its an economical dead end, because who would buy the stuff? 
Many video games already simulated this. As soon the "basic gold" becomes easily accessable the gaming community finds a "new" basic trade unit

Comment: I'm not saying computation and thought are not different, but saying that computation isn't thought because computation---at least in an electronic classical computer---happens via electrical impulses is not even a remotely valid point, because our thought wouldn't happen without electrical impulses between our neurons, whereas you can execute classical computation with gears, looms or even dominoes, no electrons required, you get many physical phenomena to compute ands and ors. Only if there is a class of programs that is more capable than Turing complete can whatever the brain is doing possibly achieve anything more, and we don't know that there is (for all we know its equivalent to an amazingly dense and power efficient computer).  We like to think were special, but what if our behaviour is simply just complex but otherwise deterministic reaction to stimuli. Its the learning process (the updating of how we react to stimuli) and how generally it can be applied that in my opinion is intelligence and were getting scary good at recreating that in the non-biological setting (especially since as usual, we're blasting ahead and leaving any emergent problems to be solved after the fact) and the extra scary thing is that we don't need to be too clever about it, we just need scale (data, memory, training operations) to rival the scale of biological evolution, but the former seems to be able to side step time scale, a lot of what has been achiever recently has arguably been achieved with a lot of brute force at training time (not just brute force, but still). Actually the intelligence I referred to is a sort of online learning, after initial training, which we don't seem to really have yet, but still (in other words, we can have intelligence emerge out of running a dumb process long enough).
